erman: habitational name from Neese (Mecklenburg-West Pomerania)."],"variants":[{"name":"McNeese","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Naois</b>, a patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Aonghus</i>, see   Angus  , after the loss of <i>gh</i> caused compensatory lengthening of the second syllable. Compare   McGinnis   and   McInnis  ."]},{"name":"Nacey","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Neese   2."]}]},{"name":"Marmaduke","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain derivation. It is generally held to be an Anglicized form of the Old Irish name <i>Mael-Maedóc</i> ‘devotee of Maedóc’. The name <i>Maedóc</i> was borne by various early Irish saints, most notably a 6th-century abbot of Clonmore and a 7th-century bishop of Ferns.  Mael-Maedóc Ó Morgair  (  1095–1148 ) was a reformer of the Church in Ireland and a friend of Bernard of Clairvaux. However, the modern Gaelic form (from  <i>c.</i>1200 ) is <i>Maol-Maodhóg</i> (pronounced ‘mul-<b>may</b>-og’), so that the name would have had to have been borrowed into English before this loss of the <i>d</i>. <i>Marmaduke</i> has never been common except in Yorkshire, where for example it was bourne by  Marmaduke Huby , abbot of Fountains, (  1495–1526 ). Its most notable bearer in recent times has been  Marmaduke Hussey  (  1923–2006 ), a former chairman of the governors of the BBC."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":69,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":71,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Marmaduke William Neepe was born in 1500, in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Sarah Berks. He died in 1580, in his hometown, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1500–1580":"1500–1580","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1525":"1525","1569":"15